Short Answer Questions

1.What is the difference between nociceptive,neuropathic and referred pain.

Silverthorn, Human Physiology, Fig 10.15

1.What is the difference between nociceptive,neuropathic and referred pain.

    • Nociceptive pain
      • Stems from tissue injury
      • Occurs when nociceptors are activated
    • Neuropathic pain
      • Stems from injuries to nerves, spinal cord, meninges, brain
    • Referred pain
      • Pain in viscera often perceived as originating from superficialsite (such as skin)
      • Results from convergence of neural pathways in CNS

Silverthorn, Human Physiology, Fig 10.15

2.Which nerve innervates the carotid sinus and carotidbody? What does this branch of the nerve sense?

Silverthorn, Human Physiology, Fig 10.15

2.Which nerve innervates the carotid sinus and carotidbody? What does this branch of the nerve sense?

The glossopharyngeal nerve. It has baroreceptors forsensing blood pressure and chemoreceptors formaintaining blood CO2 levels.

Silverthorn, Human Physiology, Fig 10.15

3.In the auditory system, what is meant by ‘tonotopy’?

Silverthorn, Human Physiology, Fig 10.15

3.In the auditory system, what is meant by ‘tonotopy’?

Tonotopy refers to a topographic organisation of thebrain centres in the auditory pathway. Neighbouringneurons in any one area tunned to tones of similarfrequency. This is a result of the sound frequencyanalysis performed by the basilar membrane.

Silverthorn, Human Physiology, Fig 10.15

3.Embellish your description by explaining theconnectivity between descending motor pathway andfollowing additional structures:

The Cerebellum receives input from motor cortex (viathe pontine nuclei and middle cerebellar peduncle).

It projects back to primary motor cortex via thethalamus (and via the middle cerebellar peduncle) .

The cerebellum also sends input to the spinal cord viathe reticulospinal and vestibulospinal tracts.

Motor Pathways Involving the Cerebellum

  • Figure 14.23

3.Embellish your description by explaining theconnectivity between descending motor pathway andfollowing additional structures:

The basal ganglia receives input from primary motorcortex: one pathway is to the striatum (direct/indirect), asecond to thesubthalamicnuclei (hyperdirect).

It provides feedback to the primary motor cortex via thethalamus.

The basal ganglia also provide descending input to thespinal column (via thependunculo-pontine nucleus) inthe reticulospinal and vestibulospinal tracts.

4.Briefly describe the mechanisms of the ear that areresponsible for converting pressure waves in the air toaction potentials in the auditory nerve under normalphysiological conditions.

4.Briefly describe the mechanisms of the ear that are responsiblefor converting pressure waves in the air to action potentials in theauditory nerve under normal physiological conditions.

Sound waves in the air cause vibrations in the tympanicmembrane. Vibrations in the tympanic membrane cause theMalleus, Incus and Stapes to vibrate. Vibrations in the Stapes causethe oval window to vibrate, which creates fluid waves in thecochlear. The fluid waves push on the flexible membranes of thecochlear duct causing the hair cells to bend. When hair cells bend,ion channels open (or close, depending on the direction) and alterneurotransmitter release. This changes action potential firing inthe cochlear nerve and this information is relayed to the brain.

Energy from the waves crosses the cochlear duct into the tympanicduct and is dissipated back into the middle ear at the roundwindow.

Silverthorn, Human Physiology, Fig 10.17

Supplementary Questions

1.Briefly explain the main functions of each of thestructures 1-6 in motor action ( you may omit the #7–the thalamus).

  1. Premotor cortex–planning of voluntary motoractions
  2. Precentral gyrus-compile program for voluntarymotor actions, and generate motor commands.
  3. Spinal tracts–convey commands to peripheralnervous system via upper motor neurons
  4. Graymatter of the spinal cord–transmit commandsto lower motor neurons. Local circuits are involved intranscribing stereotyped, repetitive motions such aslocomotion.

1.Briefly explain the main functions of each of thestructures 1-6in motor action ( you may omit the #7–the thalamus).

  1. Cerebellum–involved coordinating motor actions,making them smoother and learning motor skills.
  2. The Basal ganglia-provides regulatory loop withcortex to help decide what movements (motorcommands) to execute and when. It does this byreleasing desired movement and suppressingunwanted movement. Also critical to learning ofsuccessful or rewarding movements.
